Forgot to add you - as you were not in the original email

> Begin forwarded message:
>=20
> From: Raffaella del Prete <raffaellanz@icloud.com>
> Subject: Request for Clarification - Re: 23 Mays Road - progression of =
claims response. C90306048
> Date: 6 September 2025 at 3:04:10=E2=80=AFPM GMT+12
> To: Grant Metson <Grant.Metson@tower.co.nz>
> Cc: Claims <Claims@tower.co.nz>
>=20
> Hi Grant,
>=20
> I am following up on our visit to the property on Tuesday. I left the =
meeting feeling quite confused about several points, and I would be =
grateful if you could please clarify the following so I can properly =
understand the approach Tower is taking:
>=20
> 1. Independent expert testing
>=20
> You indicated that Tower/you will not pay for any expert testing as =
part of my preparation of the claim, as you said that is what you are =
already doing. However, I am struggling to understand this position. =
=46rom my perspective, you are preparing the claim from Tower=E2=80=99s =
side, and I have not been invited to or involved in any of the NZRSC =
assessments or discussions. This does not feel independent or =
transparent from my side.
>=20
> Given the seriousness of the fire, and the chemical involvement =
(including spa chemicals with corrosive chlorides and bromides), I am =
concerned that critical risks may be under-assessed. Could you please =
clarify why Tower would not support me in engaging independent =
engineers, hygienists, or other specialists to provide an impartial =
view?
>=20
> Further, I request that I be included in all communications with any =
assessors and 3rd parties=E2=80=94 including texts, emails, calls, and =
meetings =E2=80=94 and that these be scheduled so I have the opportunity =
to participate. This is essential for transparency and to ensure I am =
properly informed about the basis of decisions being made.
>=20
> 2. Structural elements =E2=80=93 linings and framing
>=20
> You mentioned that, in addition to demolishing and rebuilding the =
closed deck, your intention is to replace only a couple of structural =
beams and to rely on methods such as dry-ice blasting and thermal =
fogging for the bricks. =46rom a technical perspective, this seems =
inadequate because:
>=20
> Smoke odour and residue remain even on the first floor =E2=80=94 the =
least affected part of the house =E2=80=94 three months after the fire, =
suggesting deep penetration.
> The fire involved spa chemicals, creating corrosive residues =
(chlorides, bromides) likely absorbed into linings, timber framing, and =
fixings.
> Superficial cleaning, fogging, or painting over residues cannot ensure =
long-term safety or durability.
> Bricks and mortar are porous: once penetrated by smoke and chemical =
residues, they can continue to off-gas and deteriorate over time, =
undermining both habitability and structural performance.
> Similarly, timber framing, structural timbers, and plasterboard =
linings are fibrous and absorbent. Once smoke and chemical residues =
penetrate, they may release odours, compromise air quality, accelerate =
corrosion of embedded fixings, and create conditions for hidden mould or =
decay. These risks cannot be fully eliminated by surface cleaning
> Your approach appears to focus only on visible damage (e.g. darkened =
beams), while overlooking non-visible but equally serious fire, smoke, =
and water impacts. This is not appropriate, creates significant =
long-term risks, and is not aligned with Tower=E2=80=99s obligation to =
reinstate the house to an =E2=80=9Cas new=E2=80=9D standard.
>=20
> On that basis, could you clarify how retaining contaminated bricks, =
timbers, and linings meets Tower=E2=80=99s obligation to reinstate the =
property to a =E2=80=9Cas new=E2=80=9D standard? What testing and =
certification is planned to ensure these critical services are restored =
to a safe and =E2=80=9Cas new=E2=80=9D condition?
>=20
> 3. Roof assessment
>=20
> You indicated that the roof requires no work. I find this difficult to =
reconcile with the evidence:
>=20
>=20
> Large volumes of black smoke were seen coming out from all sides of =
the roof during the fire.
> A gutter was significantly heat-damaged.
> Local reporting even suggested the fire appeared to be in the roof.
>=20
> If external heat was sufficient to damage guttering, then internal =
elements such as roof cavity insulation, underlay, battens, fixings, and =
trusses may also have been affected. Could you please clarify what =
inspection methods were used to conclude the roof was undamaged? Were =
cavity inspections, intrusive checks, or residue/chemical tests =
undertaken? What testing and certification is planned to ensure these =
critical services are restored to a safe and =E2=80=9Cas new=E2=80=9D =
condition?
>=20
> 4. Services =E2=80=93 gas, electricity, and water
>=20
> I understand that you are going to test the gas unit and propose a =
plan to bring it up to new standard, which I appreciate. However, could =
you also please clarify what is planned for the  electricty system, =
which suffered significant and widespread damage and the water =
distribution system
>=20
> At present I am unclear how these critical services will be properly =
tested and reinstated. What testing and certification is planned to =
ensure these critical services are restored to a safe and =E2=80=9Cas =
new=E2=80=9D condition?
>=20
> 5. Timing and completeness of assessments
>=20
> I am also confused and  concerned that a repair plan is already being =
discussed before full assessments have been completed and before I have =
seen the NZRSC or other formal reports.
>=20
> Could you clarify why Tower is progressing toward a repair plan at =
this stage rather than awaiting intrusive testing, particularly given =
the involvement of corrosive chemicals and deep smoke penetration? What =
testing and certification is planned to ensure these critical services =
are restored to a safe and =E2=80=9Cas new=E2=80=9D condition? And what =
would be the sequencing of those to inform a realistic plan?
>=20
> In addition, is it not too risky to wait until after restructuring =
works to determine whether the house is safe and meets code =
requirements? That approach could prolong reinstatement unnecessarily, =
leaving me at greater disadvantage with accommodation costs and delays =
that are outside my control.=20
>=20
> 6. Testing and reporting
>=20
> Could you please confirm:
>=20
>=20
> What tests or assessments have actually been completed so far?
> Why, given the involvement of spa chemicals, no intrusive testing has =
been arranged?
> When the NZRSC report and other reports will be made available to me?
> What testing and certification is planned to ensure my house restored =
to a safe and =E2=80=9Cas new=E2=80=9D condition? And could you please =
provide sequencing and timings.
>=20
> 7. Accommodation suppoort
>=20
> A number of critical assessments remain outstanding =E2=80=94 =
including tests for chemical penetration, the roof structure and cavity, =
and essential services such as electricity and water. Until these are =
properly completed and confirmed, the house is uninhabitable.
>=20
> At present, my rental accommodation is being funded under the contents =
policy ($30,000 limit). However, with reinstatement not yet underway and =
key assessments still pending, it is clear this allowance will be =
insufficient. These delays are entirely outside my control.
>=20
> The Fair Insurance Code requires insurers to act fairly and not =
disadvantage customers through delay. The principle of insurance is to =
restore the insured to the pre-loss position. To avoid being placed at a =
further disadvantage, I would like to explore the following options:
>=20
>=20
> Option A: Tower agrees I may take the lead in arranging necessary =
assessments and reinstatement works, provided all works are to =E2=80=9Cas=
 new=E2=80=9D standard, meet current Building Code requirements, and =
remain within the insured sum. Tower would reimburse incurred costs =
within 15 days of invoice on a monthly basis, ensuring timely progress =
without administrative delay.
> Option B: Alternatively, Tower confirms that it will continue to cover =
my accommodation costs until the house is fully restored and habitable, =
given that ongoing delays are not of my making.
>=20
> Could you please confirm which of these approaches Tower is prepared =
to adopt, so that I am not unfairly disadvantaged by circumstances =
outside my control?
>=20
> 8. Privacy Act material
>=20
> You previously referred me to information provided under the Privacy =
Act, which I could not find. I found those two email but the links I =
received do not open or function. Could you please resend this =
information, ensuring that the links are accessible, or alternatively =
provide the documents as direct PDF/email attachments?
>=20
> Summary point
>=20
> At present, I remain unclear how Tower=E2=80=99s proposed approach =E2=80=
=94 which appears to favor superficial cleaning and limited replacement =
=E2=80=94 can reasonably restore my property to a safe, habitable, =E2=80=9C=
as new=E2=80=9D standard, particularly given the deep smoke and chemical =
penetration of bricks, timbers, and linings, the unresolved questions =
regarding the roof structure and cavity, and the uncertainty around full =
reinstatement of essential services such as electricity, water, and gas.
>=20
> I would greatly appreciate your clarification on each of these points =
so that I can properly understand how my home will be restored to a =
safe, habitable, =E2=80=9Cas new=E2=80=9D standard,
>=20
> Kind regards,
>=20
> Raffaella del Prete
>=20
>=20
