>>> On 12 Sep 2025, at 5:37=E2=80=AFPM, raffaellanz@icloud.com wrote:
>>>=20
>>> Kia ora, Grant and Claim Maager/Team,
>>> Thank you for proposing to bring the stakeholders together and =
provide a considered response. While I look forward to receiving written =
reply to my specific questions=E2=80=94could you please confirm when =
I=E2=80=99ll receive it and suggest a meeting date with an attendee =
list?  To keep things professional and efficient, could we agree on =
clear deliverables and a test-led plan? To promote progress, I=E2=80=99m =
sharing my initial questions on the documents received. I haven=E2=80=99t =
obtained professional advice yet, so I reserve the right to ask further =
questions, seek clarification, and provide additional feedback.
>>> Fairness & participation
>>> =46rom the ASURNZ report there were two assessment sessions (11 and =
21 August). I wasn=E2=80=99t invited to the briefings or either site =
inspection. I appreciate this may have been an oversight, but it leaves =
me without visibility of the brief given to ASURNZ and what they =
actually saw on the day.
>>> To balance the process, I kindly propose that Tower funds an =
independent insured-side assessment with me directly engaged; and that I =
am permitted a one-on-one session with ASURNZ, as Grant had, so I can =
brief them directly and ask questions.
>>> I=E2=80=99d also be grateful for the raw site notes and photo log =
from those two attendances, and for inclusion (with reasonable notice) =
in all future briefings, site visits, and communications.
>>> Fire chemistry & severity
>>> FENZ records show spa-pool chlorine/oxidisers stored in the origin =
cupboard, a HAZMAT requirement at dispatch, and escalation to a second =
alarm; ASURNZ also records cavity smoke migration and roof-edge heat =
(deformed soffit, melted gutter). Smoke odour remains three months =
later. Taken together, these factors indicate a heightened risk of =
corrosive/acidic residues and deep smoke penetration into cavities, =
fixings, the roof assembly, and HVAC, so a visual-only approach is not =
appropriate.
>>> As such, could you please provide a written, insurer-funded plan and =
schedule setting out methods/standards, pass criteria, dates, and named =
leads. The detailed methodology and acceptance thresholds are to be =
designed and agreed by the appropriate independent experts (hygienist, =
CPEng structural engineer, EWRB-licensed electrician/inspector, =
certifying gasfitter and HVAC technician, licensed plumber, and a =
moisture/corrosion specialist) and laboratories.  Also it is my =
understanding that AC2213 (Auckland Council Fire Reinstatement practice =
note) expects intrusive investigation and formal sign-offs where the =
primary structure or external moisture/fire systems are affected, =
including removal of wet linings/insulation, a CPEng report on the =
impact to the primary structure, LBP design/supervision where =
applicable, and s.112 BA04 considerations.
>>> I also believe that at a minimum the plan should address intrusive =
verification of roof/eaves (including underlay, battens, fixings, and =
truss nail-plates, with perimeter residue/corrosivity checks where odour =
is present); cavity assessment on the first-floor south/west elevations =
and around the fireplace (with removal/cleaning and hygienist clearance =
before re-lining where indicated); hygiene and clearance for heat-pump =
heads and the roof-space gas unit/any ducting; whole-installation =
electrical verification to AS/NZS 3000 with certification; plumbing =
system integrity testing and disinfection where indicated; moisture =
logging and corrosion/pH-chloride screening of representative =
framing/fasteners and masonry; and independent IAQ/surface clearances =
before re-lining and re-occupation.
>>> Scope adequacy
>>> =46rom the ASURNZ document, there was smoke migration into =
first-floor cavities with staining on the back of removed plasterboard, =
and roof-edge heat with deformed soffit sheeting and a melted gutter. =
The current scope appears focused on apparent damage (clean/smoke-seal, =
selective electrical checks, =E2=80=9Ctest & recommission=E2=80=9D gas) =
rather than the real damage pathways (cavities, roof assembly, services, =
corrosion).
>>> Respectfully, it is not only the visibly charred beams that can be =
compromised. Non-charred structural members, fixings, nail-plates, and =
brick/mortar exposed to smoke and/or acidic residues can degrade over =
time if not neutralised or replaced.
>>> Accordingly, could you please explain and evidence:
>>> Why full removal of plasterboard/linings (GIB) in all areas showing =
cavity smoke migration is not proposed, given deep penetration and =
potential chemical residues.
>>> The evidence-based criteria being used to decide retain vs replace =
for framing, fixings, nail-plates and insulation (including any lab =
thresholds, corrosion checks, or moisture limits).
>>> Masonry/brickwork: why cleaning/sealing is proposed instead of =
replacement of visibly affected brickwork and repointing where residues =
or acid attack are indicated; please confirm that any replacement will =
achieve an identical visual match and quality.
>>> Framing and fixings: how non-charred but smoke-exposed framing and =
fasteners will be assessed (including corrosion and surface pH/chloride =
checks), and the criteria for replacement rather than sealing.
>>> Water/firefighting impacts: what moisture mapping, drying logs, =
mould assessment/clearance, and wet-insulation replacement are planned =
for all affected areas (including ceiling/floor cavities).
>>> Basement storage and wider basement: why there is no building-works =
scope for the storage area and other basement spaces when contents from =
those areas (including items kept in sealed Sistema containers) have =
been deemed uneconomic to restore; please explain the tests relied upon =
to consider the building surfaces in those same areas salvageable, and =
provide the decontamination/repair plan for those spaces.
>>> Deck: current scope limits works to a partial deck replacement when =
heat/char/smoke exposure is recorded, while Grant has indicated the full =
deck would be rebuilt; and the tests relied upon (char-depth logs, =
moisture readings, condition of fixings/hangers/ledger-to-wall, any =
chloride/pH screening at the deck-to-wall interface). Please also =
confirm how the deck and any balustrade/handrail will meet current Code =
requirements (structure/barriers) and whether producer statements or LBP =
supervision are proposed.
>>> Deck: current scope proposes only a partial deck replacement, =
although Grant has recently indicated the full deck would be rebuilt. =
Could you please explain how a patch repair would still achieve a result =
that is =E2=80=9Creasonably equivalent to when new=E2=80=9D in =
appearance, strength and durability? Could you please also share the =
results you are relying on for: (i) char/heat checks of boards and =
joists; (ii) moisture readings and decay risk; (iii) removal and =
inspection of representative hangers, bolts and ledger fixings for =
corrosion/galvanising loss; (iv) ledger-to-wall verification, including =
flashing/weep details; (v) chloride/pH screening at the perimeter and =
fixings; and (vi) confirmation that the balustrade/handrail meets =
current requirements. If any results do not meet the engineer=E2=80=99s =
acceptance criteria, then those components will need to be replaced so =
the finished deck is truly as-new.
>>> How each relevant element=E2=80=94whether included in the current =
scope or currently omitted (e.g., walls/ceilings, framing, insulation, =
services, roof-edge components, masonry/brickwork, kitchen, basement =
storage areas, deck, roof-space plant)=E2=80=94will be addressed to =
achieve the policy standard of reinstatement =E2=80=9Creasonably =
equivalent to when new=E2=80=9D across appearance, size, functionality, =
integrity and relative quality; and, for any omitted element, the =
objective test results and reasoning relied upon for omission, plus the =
hold-points/clearances that would trigger its inclusion in the scope.
>>> Kitchen: why no kitchen works are included despite the earlier heavy =
smoke staining (later cleaned by David, engaged by Tower). Please =
provide the evidence used to exclude the kitchen (noting that post-clean =
visuals are not a clearance), the documentation of the cleaning =
undertaken (before/after photos, products/methods/SDS), the =
hygienist=E2=80=99s sampling plan for cabinetry/voids/rangehood/duct, =
and the electrical/gas/plumbing checks and clearance criteria to confirm =
the kitchen is safe for normal use.
>>> Roof/eaves and roof space: given the documented melted gutter and =
deformed soffit=E2=80=94and ongoing smoke odour=E2=80=94why is there no =
intrusive roof/eaves scope? Please confirm what was actually opened and =
inspected, what (if any) residue or corrosivity testing was done at the =
eaves/perimeter, and whether underlay, battens, fixings and truss =
nail-plates were assessed. Please also state whether perimeter wipe =
sampling is planned, whether any underlay/batten/fixing replacements are =
allowed for if contamination/heat effects are found, and whether a CPEng =
will sign off any retained structural members and roof connections. As a =
gas heating unit sits in the roof space, please confirm how =
hygiene/clearance of those components and any ducting will be achieved.
>>> Standard of reinstatement
>>> I believe that the policy requires that repairs must reinstate =
affected parts to a standard reasonably equivalent to when new =
(appearance, size, functionality, integrity, relative quality). For =
visible finishes such as brickwork, replacements should match =
identically in appearance and quality, so the final result is =
indistinguishable and durable.
>>> Building consent & AC2213
>>> ASURNZ=E2=80=99s narrative suggests no consent under Schedule =
1/s42A. My understanding is that Auckland Council=E2=80=99s AC2213 =
indicates consent is required for substantial replacement after fire and =
expects a CPEng report addressing the primary structure (including =
nail-plates/fixings at heat-affected eaves), HVAC removal/servicing, =
replacement of wet insulation, and Energy Works certificates for =
electrical/gas.
>>> Could you please:
>>> Engage a CPEng for the primary-structure report (including the =
roof/eaves zone); and
>>> Obtain Council=E2=80=99s written position for the final scope =
(consent, or a specific written exemption)? If consent is required, =
