style=3D"margin-top: 0px; margin-right: 0px; margin-bottom: 0px; =
margin-left: 0px;"><span style=3D"font-family: -webkit-system-font, =
Helvetica Neue, Helvetica, sans-serif; color:rgba(0, 0, 0, 1.0);"><b>To: =
</b></span><span style=3D"font-family: -webkit-system-font, Helvetica =
Neue, Helvetica, sans-serif;">Grant Metson =
&lt;Grant.Metson@tower.co.nz&gt;<br></span></div><div style=3D"margin-top:=
 0px; margin-right: 0px; margin-bottom: 0px; margin-left: 0px;"><span =
style=3D"font-family: -webkit-system-font, Helvetica Neue, Helvetica, =
sans-serif; color:rgba(0, 0, 0, 1.0);"><b>Cc: </b></span><span =
style=3D"font-family: -webkit-system-font, Helvetica Neue, Helvetica, =
sans-serif;">Claims =
&lt;Claims@tower.co.nz&gt;<br></span></div><br><div><meta =
http-equiv=3D"content-type" content=3D"text/html; charset=3Dutf-8"><div =
style=3D"overflow-wrap: break-word; -webkit-nbsp-mode: space; =
line-break: after-white-space;"><p>Hi Grant,</p><p>I am following up on =
our visit to the property on Tuesday. I left the meeting feeling quite =
confused about several points, and I would be grateful if you could =
please clarify the following so I can properly understand the approach =
Tower is taking:</p><p><b>1. Independent expert testing</b></p><p>You =
indicated that Tower/you will not pay for any expert testing as part of =
my preparation of the claim, as you said that is what you are already =
doing. However, I am struggling to understand this position. =46rom my =
perspective, you are preparing the claim from Tower=E2=80=99s side, and =
I have not been invited to or involved in any of the NZRSC assessments =
or discussions. This does not feel independent or transparent from my =
side.</p><p>Given the seriousness of the fire, and the chemical =
involvement (including spa chemicals with corrosive chlorides and =
bromides), I am concerned that critical risks may be under-assessed. =
Could you please clarify why Tower would not support me in engaging =
independent engineers, hygienists, or other specialists to provide an =
impartial view?</p><p data-start=3D"1135" data-end=3D"1451">Further, I =
request that I be&nbsp;<span data-start=3D"1164" =
data-end=3D"1217">included in all communications with any =
assessors</span>&nbsp;and 3rd parties=E2=80=94 including texts, emails, =
calls, and meetings =E2=80=94 and that these be scheduled so I have the =
opportunity to participate. This is essential for transparency and to =
ensure I am properly informed about the basis of decisions being =
made.</p><p><b>2. Structural elements =E2=80=93 linings and =
framing</b></p><p>You mentioned that, in addition to demolishing and =
rebuilding the closed deck, your intention is to replace only a couple =
of structural beams and to rely on methods such as dry-ice blasting and =
thermal fogging for the bricks. =46rom a technical perspective, this =
seems inadequate because:</p><div><ul class=3D"MailOutline"><li>Smoke =
odour and residue remain even on the first floor =E2=80=94 the least =
affected part of the house =E2=80=94 three months after the fire, =
suggesting deep penetration.</li><li>The fire involved spa chemicals, =
creating corrosive residues (chlorides, bromides) likely absorbed into =
linings, timber framing, and fixings.</li><li>Superficial cleaning, =
fogging, or painting over residues cannot ensure long-term safety or =
durability.</li><li>Bricks and mortar are porous: once penetrated by =
smoke and chemical residues, they can continue to off-gas and =
deteriorate over time, undermining both habitability and structural =
performance.</li><li></li><li>Similarly, timber framing, structural =
timbers, and plasterboard linings are fibrous and absorbent. Once smoke =
and chemical residues penetrate, they may release odours, compromise air =
quality, accelerate corrosion of embedded fixings, and create conditions =
for hidden mould or decay. These risks cannot be fully eliminated by =
surface cleaning</li><li>Your approach appears to focus only on visible =
damage (e.g. darkened beams), while overlooking non-visible but equally =
serious fire, smoke, and water impacts. This is not appropriate, creates =
significant long-term risks, and is not aligned with Tower=E2=80=99s =
obligation to reinstate the house to an =E2=80=9Cas new=E2=80=9D =
standard.</li></ul></div><div><br =
class=3D"webkit-block-placeholder"></div><div>On that basis, could you =
clarify how retaining contaminated bricks, timbers, and linings meets =
Tower=E2=80=99s obligation to reinstate the property to a =E2=80=9Cas =
new=E2=80=9D standard? What testing and certification is planned to =
ensure these critical services are restored to a safe and =E2=80=9Cas =
new=E2=80=9D condition?</div><div><br></div><div><b>3. Roof =
assessment</b></div><div><br =
class=3D"webkit-block-placeholder"></div><p>You indicated that the roof =
requires no work. I find this difficult to reconcile with the =
evidence:</p><div><br class=3D"webkit-block-placeholder"></div><ul =
class=3D"MailOutline"><li>Large volumes of black smoke were seen coming =
out from all sides of the roof during the fire.</li><li>A gutter was =
significantly heat-damaged.</li><li>Local reporting even suggested the =
fire appeared to be in the roof.</li></ul><div><br =
class=3D"webkit-block-placeholder"></div><p>If external heat was =
sufficient to damage guttering, then internal elements such as roof =
cavity insulation, underlay, battens, fixings, and trusses may also have =
been affected. Could you please clarify what inspection methods were =
used to conclude the roof was undamaged? Were cavity inspections, =
intrusive checks, or residue/chemical tests undertaken? What testing and =
certification is planned to ensure these critical services are restored =
to a safe and =E2=80=9Cas new=E2=80=9D condition?</p><p><b>4. Services =
=E2=80=93 gas, electricity, and water</b></p><p>I understand that you =
are going to test the gas unit and propose a plan to bring it up to new =
standard, which I appreciate. However, could you also please clarify =
what is planned for the &nbsp;electricty system, which suffered =
significant and widespread damage and the water distribution =
system</p><p>At present I am unclear how these critical services will be =
properly tested and reinstated. What testing and certification is =
planned to ensure these critical services are restored to a safe and =
=E2=80=9Cas new=E2=80=9D condition?</p><p><b>5. Timing and completeness =
of assessments</b></p><p>I am also confused and &nbsp;concerned that a =
repair plan is already being discussed before full assessments have been =
completed and before I have seen the NZRSC or other formal =
reports.</p><p>Could you clarify why Tower is progressing toward a =
repair plan at this stage rather than awaiting intrusive testing, =
particularly given the involvement of corrosive chemicals and deep smoke =
penetration? What testing and certification is planned to ensure these =
critical services are restored to a safe and =E2=80=9Cas new=E2=80=9D =
condition? And what would be the sequencing of those to inform a =
realistic plan?</p><p>In addition, is it not too risky to wait until =
after restructuring works to determine whether the house is safe and =
meets code requirements? That approach could prolong reinstatement =
unnecessarily, leaving me at greater disadvantage with accommodation =
costs and delays that are outside my control.&nbsp;</p><p><b>6. Testing =
and reporting</b></p><p>Could you please confirm:</p><div><br =
class=3D"webkit-block-placeholder"></div><ul =
class=3D"MailOutline"><li>What tests or assessments have actually been =
completed so far?</li><li>Why, given the involvement of spa chemicals, =
no intrusive testing has been arranged?</li><li>When the NZRSC report =
and other reports will be made available to me?</li><li>What testing and =
certification is planned to ensure my house restored to a safe and =E2=80=9C=
as new=E2=80=9D condition? And could you please provide sequencing and =
timings.</li></ul><div><br class=3D"webkit-block-placeholder"></div><p =
data-start=3D"286" data-end=3D"658"><b>7. Accommodation =
suppoort</b></p><p>A number of critical assessments remain outstanding =
=E2=80=94 including tests for chemical penetration, the roof structure =
and cavity, and essential services such as electricity and water. Until =
these are properly completed and confirmed, the house is =
uninhabitable.</p><p>At present, my rental accommodation is being funded =
under the contents policy ($30,000 limit). However, with reinstatement =
not yet underway and key assessments still pending, it is clear this =
allowance will be insufficient. These delays are entirely outside my =
control.</p><p>The Fair Insurance Code requires insurers to act fairly =
and not disadvantage customers through delay. The principle of insurance =
is to restore the insured to the pre-loss position. To avoid being =
placed at a further disadvantage, I would like to explore the following =
options:</p><div><br class=3D"webkit-block-placeholder"></div><ul =
class=3D"MailOutline"><li>Option A: Tower agrees I may take the lead in =
arranging necessary assessments and reinstatement works, provided all =
works are to =E2=80=9Cas new=E2=80=9D standard, meet current Building =
Code requirements, and remain within the insured sum. Tower would =
reimburse incurred costs within 15 days of invoice on a monthly basis, =
ensuring timely progress without administrative delay.</li><li>Option B: =
Alternatively, Tower confirms that it will continue to cover my =
accommodation costs until the house is fully restored and habitable, =
given that ongoing delays are not of my making.</li></ul><div><br =
class=3D"webkit-block-placeholder"></div><p>Could you please confirm =
which of these approaches Tower is prepared to adopt, so that I am not =
unfairly disadvantaged by circumstances outside my control?</p><p><b>8. =
Privacy Act material</b></p><p>You previously referred me to information =
provided under the Privacy Act, which I could not find. I found those =
two email but the links I received do not open or function. Could you =
please resend this information, ensuring that the links are accessible, =
or alternatively provide the documents as direct PDF/email =
attachments?</p><p><b>Summary point</b></p><p>At present, I remain =
unclear how Tower=E2=80=99s proposed approach =E2=80=94 which appears to =
favor superficial cleaning and limited replacement =E2=80=94 can =
reasonably restore my property to a safe, habitable, =E2=80=9Cas new=E2=80=
=9D standard, particularly given the deep smoke and chemical penetration =
of bricks, timbers, and linings, the unresolved questions regarding the =
roof structure and cavity, and the uncertainty around full reinstatement =
of essential services such as electricity, water, and gas.</p><p>I would =
greatly appreciate your clarification on each of these points so that I =
can properly understand how my home will be restored to a safe, =
habitable, =E2=80=9Cas new=E2=80=9D standard,</p><p>Kind =
regards,</p><p>Raffaella del Prete</p><div><br></div><div><blockquote =
type=3D"cite"><div>On 1 Sep 2025, at 7:41=E2=80=AFPM, Grant Metson =
