dir=3D"auto"><br id=3D"lineBreakAtBeginningOfSignature"><div =
dir=3D"ltr">Hi Zach, could you please provide me with an update =
?</div><div dir=3D"ltr"><br></div><div dir=3D"ltr"><br></div><div =
dir=3D"ltr"><br></div><blockquote type=3D"cite"><div =
dir=3D"ltr"><div><div><br><blockquote type=3D"cite"><div>On 12 Sep 2025, =
at 5:37=E2=80=AFPM, raffaellanz@icloud.com wrote:</div><br =
class=3D"Apple-interchange-newline"><div><meta charset=3D"UTF-8"><div =
class=3D"WordSection1" style=3D"page: WordSection1; caret-color: rgb(0, =
0, 0); font-family: Helvetica; font-size: 12px; font-style: normal; =
font-variant-caps: normal; font-weight: 400; letter-spacing: normal; =
text-align: start; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: =
normal; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; =
text-decoration: none;"><div style=3D"margin: 0in; font-size: 10pt; =
font-family: Aptos, sans-serif;"><span style=3D"">Kia ora, Grant and =
Claim Maager/Team,</span><span style=3D"font-size: 12pt; color: rgb(33, =
33, 33);"><o:p></o:p></span></div><div style=3D"margin: 0in; font-size: =
10pt; font-family: Aptos, sans-serif;">Thank you for proposing to bring =
the stakeholders together and provide a considered response. While I =
look forward to receiving written reply to my specific questions=E2=80=94c=
ould you please confirm when I=E2=80=99ll receive it and suggest a =
meeting date with an attendee list? &nbsp;To keep things professional =
and efficient, could we agree on clear deliverables and a test-led plan? =
To promote progress, I=E2=80=99m sharing my initial questions on the =
documents received. I haven=E2=80=99t obtained professional advice yet, =
so I reserve the right to ask further questions, seek clarification, and =
provide additional feedback.</div><div style=3D"margin: 0in; font-size: =
10pt; font-family: Aptos, sans-serif;"><u><span style=3D"">Fairness =
&amp; participation</span></u><span style=3D""><br>=46rom the ASURNZ =
report there were two assessment sessions (11 and 21 August). I wasn=E2=80=
=99t invited to the briefings or either site inspection. I appreciate =
this may have been an oversight, but it leaves me without visibility of =
the brief given to ASURNZ and what they actually saw on the day.<br>To =
balance the process, I kindly propose that Tower funds an independent =
insured-side assessment with me directly engaged; and that I am =
permitted a one-on-one session with ASURNZ, as Grant had, so I can brief =
them directly and ask questions.<br>I=E2=80=99d also be grateful for the =
raw site notes and photo log from those two attendances, and for =
inclusion (with reasonable notice) in all future briefings, site visits, =
and communications.</span><span style=3D"font-size: 12pt; color: rgb(33, =
33, 33);"><o:p></o:p></span></div><div style=3D"margin: 0in; font-size: =
10pt; font-family: Aptos, sans-serif;"><u><span style=3D"">Fire =
chemistry &amp; severity</span></u><span style=3D""><br></span><span =
style=3D"color: rgb(33, 33, 33);">FENZ records show spa-pool =
chlorine/oxidisers stored in the origin cupboard, a HAZMAT requirement =
at dispatch, and escalation to a second alarm; ASURNZ also records =
cavity smoke migration and roof-edge heat (deformed soffit, melted =
gutter). Smoke odour remains three months later. Taken together, these =
factors indicate a heightened risk of corrosive/acidic residues and deep =
smoke penetration into cavities, fixings, the roof assembly, and HVAC, =
so a visual-only approach is not appropriate.</span><span =
style=3D"font-size: 12pt; color: rgb(33, 33, =
33);"><o:p></o:p></span></div><div style=3D"margin: 0in; font-size: =
10pt; font-family: Aptos, sans-serif;"><span style=3D"color: rgb(33, 33, =
33);">As such, could you please provide a written, insurer-funded plan =
and schedule setting out methods/standards, pass criteria, dates, and =
named leads. The detailed methodology and acceptance thresholds are to =
be designed and agreed by the appropriate independent experts =
(hygienist, CPEng structural engineer, EWRB-licensed =
electrician/inspector, certifying gasfitter and HVAC technician, =
licensed plumber, and a moisture/corrosion specialist) and laboratories. =
&nbsp;Also it is my understanding that AC2213 (Auckland Council Fire =
Reinstatement practice note) expects intrusive investigation and formal =
sign-offs where the primary structure or external moisture/fire systems =
are affected, including removal of wet linings/insulation, a CPEng =
report on the impact to the primary structure, LBP design/supervision =
where applicable, and s.112 BA04 considerations.</span><span =
style=3D"font-size: 12pt; color: rgb(33, 33, =
33);"><o:p></o:p></span></div><div style=3D"margin: 0in; font-size: =
10pt; font-family: Aptos, sans-serif;"><span style=3D"color: rgb(33, 33, =
33);">I also believe that at a minimum&nbsp;the plan should address =
intrusive verification of roof/eaves (including underlay, battens, =
fixings, and truss nail-plates, with perimeter residue/corrosivity =
checks where odour is present); cavity assessment on the first-floor =
south/west elevations and around the fireplace (with removal/cleaning =
and hygienist clearance before re-lining where indicated); hygiene and =
clearance for heat-pump heads and the roof-space gas unit/any ducting; =
whole-installation electrical verification to AS/NZS 3000 with =
certification; plumbing system integrity testing and disinfection where =
indicated; moisture logging and corrosion/pH-chloride screening of =
representative framing/fasteners and masonry; and independent =
IAQ/surface clearances before re-lining and re-occupation.</span><span =
style=3D"font-size: 12pt; color: rgb(33, 33, =
33);"><o:p></o:p></span></div><div style=3D"margin: 0in; font-size: =
10pt; font-family: Aptos, sans-serif;"><u><span style=3D"">Scope =
adequacy</span></u><span style=3D""><br>=46rom the ASURNZ document, =
there was smoke migration into first-floor cavities with staining on the =
back of removed plasterboard, and roof-edge heat with deformed soffit =
sheeting and a melted gutter. The current scope appears focused on =
apparent damage (clean/smoke-seal, selective electrical checks, =E2=80=9Ct=
est &amp; recommission=E2=80=9D gas) rather than the real damage =
pathways (cavities, roof assembly, services, =
corrosion).<br>Respectfully, it is not only the visibly charred beams =
that can be compromised. Non-charred structural members, fixings, =
nail-plates, and brick/mortar exposed to smoke and/or acidic residues =
can degrade over time if not neutralised or replaced.</span><span =
style=3D"font-size: 12pt; color: rgb(33, 33, =
33);"><o:p></o:p></span></div><div style=3D"margin: 0in; font-size: =
10pt; font-family: Aptos, sans-serif;"><span style=3D"">Accordingly, =
could you please explain and evidence:</span><span style=3D"font-size: =
12pt; color: rgb(33, 33, 33);"><o:p></o:p></span></div><ul type=3D"disc" =
style=3D"margin-bottom: 0in;"><li class=3D"MsoNormal" style=3D"margin: =
0in; font-size: 10pt; font-family: Aptos, sans-serif;">Why full removal =
of plasterboard/linings (GIB) in all areas showing cavity smoke =
migration is not proposed, given deep penetration and potential chemical =
residues.<span style=3D"font-size: 12pt;"><o:p></o:p></span></li><li =
class=3D"MsoNormal" style=3D"margin: 0in; font-size: 10pt; font-family: =
Aptos, sans-serif;">The evidence-based criteria being used to decide =
retain vs replace for framing, fixings, nail-plates and insulation =
(including any lab thresholds, corrosion checks,<span =
class=3D"Apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span><span style=3D"font-size: =
7.5pt;">or</span><span =
class=3D"Apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span>moisture limits).<span =
style=3D"font-size: 12pt;"><o:p></o:p></span></li><li class=3D"MsoNormal" =
style=3D"margin: 0in; font-size: 10pt; font-family: Aptos, =
sans-serif;">Masonry/brickwork: why cleaning/sealing is proposed instead =
of replacement of visibly affected brickwork and repointing where =
residues or acid attack are indicated; please confirm that any =
replacement will achieve an identical visual match and quality.<span =
style=3D"font-size: 12pt;"><o:p></o:p></span></li><li class=3D"MsoNormal" =
style=3D"margin: 0in; font-size: 10pt; font-family: Aptos, =
sans-serif;">Framing and fixings: how non-charred but smoke-exposed =
framing and fasteners will be assessed (including corrosion and surface =
pH/chloride checks), and the criteria for replacement rather than =
sealing.<span style=3D"font-size: 12pt;"><o:p></o:p></span></li><li =
class=3D"MsoNormal" style=3D"margin: 0in; font-size: 10pt; font-family: =
Aptos, sans-serif;">Water/firefighting impacts: what moisture mapping, =
drying logs, mould assessment/clearance, and wet-insulation replacement =
are planned for all affected areas (including ceiling/floor =
cavities).<span style=3D"font-size: 12pt;"><o:p></o:p></span></li><li =
class=3D"MsoNormal" style=3D"margin: 0in; font-size: 10pt; font-family: =
Aptos, sans-serif;">Basement storage and wider basement: why there is no =
building-works scope for the storage area and other basement spaces when =
contents from those areas (including items kept in sealed Sistema =
containers) have been deemed uneconomic to restore; please explain the =
tests relied upon to consider the building surfaces in those same areas =
salvageable, and provide the decontamination/repair plan for those =
spaces.<span style=3D"font-size: 12pt;"><o:p></o:p></span></li><li =
class=3D"MsoNormal" style=3D"margin: 0in; font-size: 10pt; font-family: =
Aptos, sans-serif;">Deck: current scope limits works to a partial deck =
replacement when heat/char/smoke exposure is recorded, while Grant has =
indicated the full deck would be rebuilt; and the tests relied upon =
(char-depth logs, moisture readings, condition of =
fixings/hangers/ledger-to-wall, any chloride/pH screening at the =
deck-to-wall interface). Please also confirm how the deck and any =
balustrade/handrail will meet current Code requirements =
(structure/barriers) and whether producer statements or LBP supervision =
are proposed.<span style=3D"font-size: 12pt;"><o:p></o:p></span></li><li =
class=3D"MsoNormal" style=3D"margin: 0in; font-size: 10pt; font-family: =
Aptos, sans-serif;"><span style=3D"color: windowtext;">Deck: current =
scope proposes only a partial deck replacement, although Grant has =
recently indicated the full deck would be rebuilt. Could you please =
explain how a patch repair would still achieve a result that is =
=E2=80=9Creasonably equivalent to when new=E2=80=9D in appearance, =
strength and durability? Could you please also share the results you are =
relying on for: (i) char/heat checks of boards and joists; (ii) moisture =
readings and decay risk; (iii) removal and inspection of representative =
hangers, bolts and ledger fixings for corrosion/galvanising loss; (iv) =
ledger-to-wall verification, including flashing/weep details; (v) =
chloride/pH screening at the perimeter and fixings; and (vi) =
confirmation that the balustrade/handrail meets current requirements. If =
any results do not meet the engineer=E2=80=99s acceptance criteria, then =
those components will need to be replaced so the finished deck is truly =
as-new.</span><span style=3D"font-size: =
12pt;"><o:p></o:p></span></li><li class=3D"MsoNormal" style=3D"margin: =
0in; font-size: 10pt; font-family: Aptos, sans-serif;">How each relevant =
element=E2=80=94whether included in the current scope or currently =
omitted (e.g., walls/ceilings, framing, insulation, services, roof-edge =
components, masonry/brickwork, kitchen, basement storage areas, deck, =
roof-space plant)=E2=80=94will be addressed to achieve the policy =
standard of reinstatement =E2=80=9Creasonably equivalent to when new=E2=80=
=9D across appearance, size, functionality, integrity and relative =
quality; and, for any omitted element, the objective test results and =
reasoning relied upon for omission, plus the hold-points/clearances that =
would trigger its inclusion in the scope.<span style=3D"font-size: =
12pt;"><o:p></o:p></span></li><li class=3D"MsoNormal" style=3D"margin: =
0in; font-size: 10pt; font-family: Aptos, sans-serif;">Kitchen: why no =
kitchen works are included despite the earlier heavy smoke staining =
(later cleaned by David, engaged by Tower). Please provide the evidence =
used to exclude the kitchen (noting that post-clean visuals are not a =
clearance), the documentation of the cleaning undertaken (before/after =
photos, products/methods/SDS), the hygienist=E2=80=99s sampling plan for =
cabinetry/voids/rangehood/duct, and the electrical/gas/plumbing checks =
and clearance criteria to confirm the kitchen is safe for normal =
use.<span style=3D"font-size: 12pt;"><o:p></o:p></span></li><li =
class=3D"MsoNormal" style=3D"margin: 0in; font-size: 10pt; font-family: =
Aptos, sans-serif;">Roof/eaves and roof space: given the documented =
melted gutter and deformed soffit=E2=80=94and ongoing smoke odour=E2=80=94=
why is there no intrusive roof/eaves scope? Please confirm what was =
actually opened and inspected, what (if any) residue or corrosivity =
testing was done at the eaves/perimeter, and whether underlay, battens, =
fixings and truss nail-plates were assessed. Please also state whether =
perimeter wipe sampling is planned, whether any underlay/batten/fixing =
replacements are allowed for if contamination/heat effects are found, =
and whether a CPEng will sign off any retained structural members and =
roof connections. As a gas heating unit sits in the roof space, please =
confirm how hygiene/clearance of those components and any ducting will =
be achieved.<span style=3D"font-size: =
12pt;"><o:p></o:p></span></li></ul><div style=3D"margin: 0in; font-size: =
10pt; font-family: Aptos, sans-serif;"><u><span style=3D"">Standard of =
reinstatement</span></u><span style=3D""><br></span><span style=3D"color: =
rgb(33, 33, 33);">I believe that the policy requires that&nbsp;repairs =
must reinstate affected parts to a standard reasonably equivalent to =
when new (appearance, size, functionality, integrity, relative quality). =
For visible finishes such as brickwork, replacements should match =
identically in appearance and quality, so the final result is =
indistinguishable and durable.</span><span style=3D"font-size: 12pt; =
color: rgb(33, 33, 33);"><o:p></o:p></span></div><div style=3D"margin: =
0in; font-size: 10pt; font-family: Aptos, sans-serif;"><u><span =
style=3D"">Building consent &amp; AC2213</span></u><span =
style=3D""><br>ASURNZ=E2=80=99s narrative suggests no consent under =
Schedule 1/s42A. My understanding is that Auckland Council=E2=80=99s =
AC2213 indicates consent is required for substantial replacement after =
fire and expects a CPEng report addressing the primary structure =
(including nail-plates/fixings at heat-affected eaves), HVAC =
removal/servicing, replacement of wet insulation, and Energy Works =
certificates for electrical/gas.<br>Could you please:</span><span =
style=3D"font-size: 12pt; color: rgb(33, 33, =
33);"><o:p></o:p></span></div><ul type=3D"disc" style=3D"margin-bottom: =
0in;"><li class=3D"MsoNormal" style=3D"margin: 0in; font-size: 10pt; =
font-family: Aptos, sans-serif;">Engage a CPEng for the =
primary-structure report (including the roof/eaves zone); and<span =
style=3D"font-size: 12pt;"><o:p></o:p></span></li><li class=3D"MsoNormal" =
style=3D"margin: 0in; font-size: 10pt; font-family: Aptos, =
sans-serif;">Obtain Council=E2=80=99s written position for the final =
scope (consent, or a specific written exemption)? If consent is =
required, please outline LBPs/Producer Statements and inspections.<span =
style=3D"font-size: 12pt;"><o:p></o:p></span></li></ul><div =
style=3D"margin: 0in; font-size: 10pt; font-family: Aptos, =
sans-serif;"><u><span style=3D"">Decision-gate and =
transparency</span></u><span style=3D""><br>No repair work or close-ups =
should occur until all expert reports and clearances above are completed =
and shared, and we have agreed what needs to be done. Please schedule =
all inspections and tests with me present, and provide the raw lab =
reports and photo logs.</span><span style=3D"font-size: 12pt; color: =
rgb(33, 33, 33);"><o:p></o:p></span></div><div style=3D"margin: 0in; =
