class=3D"Apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span>wrote:<o:p></o:p></div></div>=
<div style=3D"margin: 0in; font-size: 12pt; font-family: Aptos, =
sans-serif;"><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></div><div><div><div style=3D"margin: 0in; =
font-size: 12pt; font-family: Aptos, sans-serif;"><span =
style=3D"font-size: 10pt;">Kia ora, Grant and Claim =
Maager/Team,<o:p></o:p></span></div></div><div><div style=3D"margin: =
0in; font-size: 12pt; font-family: Aptos, sans-serif;"><span =
style=3D"font-size: 10pt;">Thank you for proposing to bring the =
stakeholders together and provide a considered response. While I look =
forward to receiving written reply to my specific questions=E2=80=94could =
you please confirm when I=E2=80=99ll receive it and suggest a meeting =
date with an attendee list? &nbsp;To keep things professional and =
efficient, could we agree on clear deliverables and a test-led plan? To =
promote progress, I=E2=80=99m sharing my initial questions on the =
documents received. I haven=E2=80=99t obtained professional advice yet, =
so I reserve the right to ask further questions, seek clarification, and =
provide additional feedback.<o:p></o:p></span></div></div><div><div =
style=3D"margin: 0in; font-size: 12pt; font-family: Aptos, =
sans-serif;"><u><span style=3D"font-size: 10pt;">Fairness &amp; =
participation</span></u><span style=3D"font-size: 10pt;"><br>=46rom the =
ASURNZ report there were two assessment sessions (11 and 21 August). I =
wasn=E2=80=99t invited to the briefings or either site inspection. I =
appreciate this may have been an oversight, but it leaves me without =
visibility of the brief given to ASURNZ and what they actually saw on =
the day.<br>To balance the process, I kindly propose that Tower funds an =
independent insured-side assessment with me directly engaged; and that I =
am permitted a one-on-one session with ASURNZ, as Grant had, so I can =
brief them directly and ask questions.<br>I=E2=80=99d also be grateful =
for the raw site notes and photo log from those two attendances, and for =
inclusion (with reasonable notice) in all future briefings, site visits, =
and communications.<o:p></o:p></span></div></div><div><div =
style=3D"margin: 0in; font-size: 12pt; font-family: Aptos, =
sans-serif;"><u><span style=3D"font-size: 10pt;">Fire chemistry &amp; =
severity</span></u><span style=3D"font-size: 10pt;"><br><span =
style=3D"color: rgb(33, 33, 33);">FENZ records show spa-pool =
chlorine/oxidisers stored in the origin cupboard, a HAZMAT requirement =
at dispatch, and escalation to a second alarm; ASURNZ also records =
cavity smoke migration and roof-edge heat (deformed soffit, melted =
gutter). Smoke odour remains three months later. Taken together, these =
factors indicate a heightened risk of corrosive/acidic residues and deep =
smoke penetration into cavities, fixings, the roof assembly, and HVAC, =
so a visual-only approach is not =
appropriate.</span><o:p></o:p></span></div></div><div><div =
style=3D"margin: 0in; font-size: 12pt; font-family: Aptos, =
sans-serif;"><span style=3D"font-size: 10pt; color: rgb(33, 33, 33);">As =
such, could you please provide a written, insurer-funded plan and =
schedule setting out methods/standards, pass criteria, dates, and named =
leads. The detailed methodology and acceptance thresholds are to be =
designed and agreed by the appropriate independent experts (hygienist, =
CPEng structural engineer, EWRB-licensed electrician/inspector, =
certifying gasfitter and HVAC technician, licensed plumber, and a =
moisture/corrosion specialist) and laboratories. &nbsp;Also it is my =
understanding that AC2213 (Auckland Council Fire Reinstatement practice =
note) expects intrusive investigation and formal sign-offs where the =
primary structure or external moisture/fire systems are affected, =
including removal of wet linings/insulation, a CPEng report on the =
impact to the primary structure, LBP design/supervision where =
applicable, and s.112 BA04 considerations.</span><span style=3D"font-size:=
 10pt;"><o:p></o:p></span></div></div><div><div style=3D"margin: 0in; =
font-size: 12pt; font-family: Aptos, sans-serif;"><span =
style=3D"font-size: 10pt; color: rgb(33, 33, 33);">I also believe that =
at a minimum&nbsp;the plan should address intrusive verification of =
roof/eaves (including underlay, battens, fixings, and truss nail-plates, =
with perimeter residue/corrosivity checks where odour is present); =
cavity assessment on the first-floor south/west elevations and around =
the fireplace (with removal/cleaning and hygienist clearance before =
re-lining where indicated); hygiene and clearance for heat-pump heads =
and the roof-space gas unit/any ducting; whole-installation electrical =
verification to AS/NZS 3000 with certification; plumbing system =
integrity testing and disinfection where indicated; moisture logging and =
corrosion/pH-chloride screening of representative framing/fasteners and =
masonry; and independent IAQ/surface clearances before re-lining and =
re-occupation.</span><span style=3D"font-size: =
10pt;"><o:p></o:p></span></div></div><div><div style=3D"margin: 0in; =
font-size: 12pt; font-family: Aptos, sans-serif;"><u><span =
style=3D"font-size: 10pt;">Scope adequacy</span></u><span =
style=3D"font-size: 10pt;"><br>=46rom the ASURNZ document, there was =
smoke migration into first-floor cavities with staining on the back of =
removed plasterboard, and roof-edge heat with deformed soffit sheeting =
and a melted gutter. The current scope appears focused on apparent =
damage (clean/smoke-seal, selective electrical checks, =E2=80=9Ctest =
&amp; recommission=E2=80=9D gas) rather than the real damage pathways =
(cavities, roof assembly, services, corrosion).<br>Respectfully, it is =
not only the visibly charred beams that can be compromised. Non-charred =
structural members, fixings, nail-plates, and brick/mortar exposed to =
smoke and/or acidic residues can degrade over time if not neutralised or =
replaced.<o:p></o:p></span></div></div><div><div style=3D"margin: 0in; =
font-size: 12pt; font-family: Aptos, sans-serif;"><span =
style=3D"font-size: 10pt;">Accordingly, could you please explain and =
evidence:<o:p></o:p></span></div></div><ul type=3D"disc" =
style=3D"margin-bottom: 0in; margin-top: 0in;"><li class=3D"MsoNormal" =
style=3D"margin: 0in; font-size: 12pt; font-family: Aptos, =
sans-serif;"><span style=3D"font-size: 10pt;">Why full removal of =
plasterboard/linings (GIB) in all areas showing cavity smoke migration =
is not proposed, given deep penetration and potential chemical =
residues.<o:p></o:p></span></li><li class=3D"MsoNormal" style=3D"margin: =
0in; font-size: 12pt; font-family: Aptos, sans-serif;"><span =
style=3D"font-size: 10pt;">The evidence-based criteria being used to =
decide retain vs replace for framing, fixings, nail-plates and =
insulation (including any lab thresholds, corrosion checks,<span =
class=3D"apple-converted-space">&nbsp;</span></span><span =
style=3D"font-size: 7.5pt;">or</span><span =
class=3D"apple-converted-space"><span style=3D"font-size: =
10pt;">&nbsp;</span></span><span style=3D"font-size: 10pt;">moisture =
limits).<o:p></o:p></span></li><li class=3D"MsoNormal" style=3D"margin: =
0in; font-size: 12pt; font-family: Aptos, sans-serif;"><span =
style=3D"font-size: 10pt;">Masonry/brickwork: why cleaning/sealing is =
proposed instead of replacement of visibly affected brickwork and =
repointing where residues or acid attack are indicated; please confirm =
that any replacement will achieve an identical visual match and =
quality.<o:p></o:p></span></li><li class=3D"MsoNormal" style=3D"margin: =
0in; font-size: 12pt; font-family: Aptos, sans-serif;"><span =
style=3D"font-size: 10pt;">Framing and fixings: how non-charred but =
smoke-exposed framing and fasteners will be assessed (including =
corrosion and surface pH/chloride checks), and the criteria for =
replacement rather than sealing.<o:p></o:p></span></li><li =
class=3D"MsoNormal" style=3D"margin: 0in; font-size: 12pt; font-family: =
Aptos, sans-serif;"><span style=3D"font-size: 10pt;">Water/firefighting =
impacts: what moisture mapping, drying logs, mould assessment/clearance, =
and wet-insulation replacement are planned for all affected areas =
(including ceiling/floor cavities).<o:p></o:p></span></li><li =
class=3D"MsoNormal" style=3D"margin: 0in; font-size: 12pt; font-family: =
Aptos, sans-serif;"><span style=3D"font-size: 10pt;">Basement storage =
and wider basement: why there is no building-works scope for the storage =
area and other basement spaces when contents from those areas (including =
items kept in sealed Sistema containers) have been deemed uneconomic to =
restore; please explain the tests relied upon to consider the building =
surfaces in those same areas salvageable, and provide the =
decontamination/repair plan for those spaces.<o:p></o:p></span></li><li =
class=3D"MsoNormal" style=3D"margin: 0in; font-size: 12pt; font-family: =
Aptos, sans-serif;"><span style=3D"font-size: 10pt;">Deck: current scope =
limits works to a partial deck replacement when heat/char/smoke exposure =
is recorded, while Grant has indicated the full deck would be rebuilt; =
and the tests relied upon (char-depth logs, moisture readings, condition =
of fixings/hangers/ledger-to-wall, any chloride/pH screening at the =
deck-to-wall interface). Please also confirm how the deck and any =
balustrade/handrail will meet current Code requirements =
(structure/barriers) and whether producer statements or LBP supervision =
are proposed.<o:p></o:p></span></li><li class=3D"MsoNormal" =
style=3D"margin: 0in; font-size: 12pt; font-family: Aptos, =
sans-serif;"><span style=3D"font-size: 10pt;">Deck: current scope =
proposes only a partial deck replacement, although Grant has recently =
indicated the full deck would be rebuilt. Could you please explain how a =
patch repair would still achieve a result that is =E2=80=9Creasonably =
equivalent to when new=E2=80=9D in appearance, strength and durability? =
Could you please also share the results you are relying on for: (i) =
char/heat checks of boards and joists; (ii) moisture readings and decay =
risk; (iii) removal and inspection of representative hangers, bolts and =
ledger fixings for corrosion/galvanising loss; (iv) ledger-to-wall =
verification, including flashing/weep details; (v) chloride/pH screening =
at the perimeter and fixings; and (vi) confirmation that the =
balustrade/handrail meets current requirements. If any results do not =
meet the engineer=E2=80=99s acceptance criteria, then those components =
will need to be replaced so the finished deck is truly =
as-new.<o:p></o:p></span></li><li class=3D"MsoNormal" style=3D"margin: =
0in; font-size: 12pt; font-family: Aptos, sans-serif;"><span =
style=3D"font-size: 10pt;">How each relevant element=E2=80=94whether =
included in the current scope or currently omitted (e.g., =
walls/ceilings, framing, insulation, services, roof-edge components, =
masonry/brickwork, kitchen, basement storage areas, deck, roof-space =
plant)=E2=80=94will be addressed to achieve the policy standard of =
reinstatement =E2=80=9Creasonably equivalent to when new=E2=80=9D across =
appearance, size, functionality, integrity and relative quality; and, =
for any omitted element, the objective test results and reasoning relied =
upon for omission, plus the hold-points/clearances that would trigger =
its inclusion in the scope.<o:p></o:p></span></li><li class=3D"MsoNormal" =
style=3D"margin: 0in; font-size: 12pt; font-family: Aptos, =
sans-serif;"><span style=3D"font-size: 10pt;">Kitchen: why no kitchen =
works are included despite the earlier heavy smoke staining (later =
cleaned by David, engaged by Tower). Please provide the evidence used to =
exclude the kitchen (noting that post-clean visuals are not a =
clearance), the documentation of the cleaning undertaken (before/after =
photos, products/methods/SDS), the hygienist=E2=80=99s sampling plan for =
cabinetry/voids/rangehood/duct, and the electrical/gas/plumbing checks =
and clearance criteria to confirm the kitchen is safe for normal =
use.<o:p></o:p></span></li><li class=3D"MsoNormal" style=3D"margin: 0in; =
font-size: 12pt; font-family: Aptos, sans-serif;"><span =
style=3D"font-size: 10pt;">Roof/eaves and roof space: given the =
documented melted gutter and deformed soffit=E2=80=94and ongoing smoke =
odour=E2=80=94why is there no intrusive roof/eaves scope? Please confirm =
what was actually opened and inspected, what (if any) residue or =
corrosivity testing was done at the eaves/perimeter, and whether =
underlay, battens, fixings and truss nail-plates were assessed. Please =
also state whether perimeter wipe sampling is planned, whether any =
underlay/batten/fixing replacements are allowed for if =
contamination/heat effects are found, and whether a CPEng will sign off =
any retained structural members and roof connections. As a gas heating =
unit sits in the roof space, please confirm how hygiene/clearance of =
those components and any ducting will be =
achieved.<o:p></o:p></span></li></ul><div><div style=3D"margin: 0in; =
font-size: 12pt; font-family: Aptos, sans-serif;"><u><span =
style=3D"font-size: 10pt;">Standard of reinstatement</span></u><span =
style=3D"font-size: 10pt;"><br><span style=3D"color: rgb(33, 33, 33);">I =
believe that the policy requires that&nbsp;repairs must reinstate =
affected parts to a standard reasonably equivalent to when new =
(appearance, size, functionality, integrity, relative quality). For =
visible finishes such as brickwork, replacements should match =
identically in appearance and quality, so the final result is =
indistinguishable and =
durable.</span><o:p></o:p></span></div></div><div><div style=3D"margin: =
0in; font-size: 12pt; font-family: Aptos, sans-serif;"><u><span =
style=3D"font-size: 10pt;">Building consent &amp; AC2213</span></u><span =
style=3D"font-size: 10pt;"><br>ASURNZ=E2=80=99s narrative suggests no =
consent under Schedule 1/s42A. My understanding is that Auckland =
Council=E2=80=99s AC2213 indicates consent is required for substantial =
replacement after fire and expects a CPEng report addressing the primary =
structure (including nail-plates/fixings at heat-affected eaves), HVAC =
removal/servicing, replacement of wet insulation, and Energy Works =
certificates for electrical/gas.<br>Could you =
please:<o:p></o:p></span></div></div><ul type=3D"disc" =
